<body>
  <div class="container">
    <h1>Car Axle Guide</h1>

    <!-- Purpose Section -->
    <div class="card">
      <h2>Purpose</h2>
      <p>The axle is a crucial component of the car's drivetrain, responsible for transferring power from the engine to the wheels. It supports the weight of the vehicle and ensures smooth movement by allowing the wheels to rotate.</p>
    </div>

    <!-- Types of Axles Section -->
    <div class="card">
      <h2>Types of Axles</h2>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Live Axle:</strong> Transmits power to the wheels and supports the vehicle's weight. Common in trucks and older vehicles.</li>
        <li><strong>Dead Axle:</strong> Does not transmit power but supports the vehicle's weight. Often found in trailers.</li>
        <li><strong>Front Axle:</strong> Located at the front of the vehicle, responsible for steering and supporting the front wheels.</li>
        <li><strong>Rear Axle:</strong> Located at the rear of the vehicle, responsible for driving the rear wheels in rear-wheel-drive vehicles.</li>
        <li><strong>Stub Axle:</strong> Connects the wheels to the front axle in steering systems.</li>
      </ul>
    </div>

    <!-- Components Section -->
    <div class="card">
      <h2>Components</h2>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Axle Shaft:</strong> The main rod that transfers power from the differential to the wheels.</li>
        <li><strong>Differential:</strong> Distributes power to the wheels while allowing them to rotate at different speeds.</li>
        <li><strong>CV Joints (Constant Velocity Joints):</strong> Allow the axle to flex and transmit power smoothly, especially in front-wheel-drive vehicles.</li>
        <li><strong>Bearings:</strong> Reduce friction and support the axle's rotation.</li>
        <li><strong>Hub:</strong> Connects the axle to the wheel, allowing it to rotate.</li>
      </ul>
    </div>

    <!-- Maintenance Section -->
    <div class="card">
      <h2>Maintenance</h2>
      <ul>
        <li>Regularly inspect the axle for signs of wear, such as cracks or bends.</li>
        <li>Check the CV joints for damage or leaks and replace them if necessary.</li>
        <li>Lubricate the axle and its components to reduce friction and prevent wear.</li>
        <li>Listen for unusual noises (e.g., clicking or grinding) that may indicate axle issues.</li>
        <li>Ensure the axle alignment is correct to prevent uneven tire wear and handling issues.</li>
      </ul>
    </div>

    <!-- Signs of Axle Issues Section -->
    <div class="card">
      <h2>Signs of Axle Issues</h2>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Clicking Noises:</strong> A clicking sound when turning may indicate a damaged CV joint.</li>
        <li><strong>Vibrations:</strong> Excessive vibrations while driving may signal a bent or damaged axle.</li>
        <li><strong>Leaking Grease:</strong> Grease around the CV joints or axle boots indicates a leak.</li>
        <li><strong>Difficulty Steering:</strong> A damaged front axle can cause steering problems.</li>
        <li><strong>Uneven Tire Wear:</strong> Misaligned axles can cause uneven tire wear.</li>
      </ul>
    </div>

